1
00:01:17,875 --> 00:01:20,138
Dartmoor prison.

2
00:01:20,204 --> 00:01:23,307
Isolated from the outside world

3
00:01:23,373 --> 00:01:25,432
by walls of granite.

4
00:01:35,838 --> 00:01:37,731
They say you could get out of here

5
00:01:37,797 --> 00:01:40,610
by merely telling what you know.

6
00:01:40,676 --> 00:01:45,279
You may or may not be
another Scotland Yard bloke

7
00:01:45,345 --> 00:01:49,827
but I'll give you the same
answer I gave the others.

8
00:01:49,893 --> 00:01:54,365
I still have two years,
eight months and six days left

9
00:01:54,431 --> 00:01:56,984
in which to make musical boxes

10
00:01:57,050 --> 00:01:58,622
that will be sold at auction

11
00:01:58,689 --> 00:02:03,332
for the benefit of this
delightful sanctuary.

12
00:02:03,398 --> 00:02:05,237
And I intend to sell them.

13
00:02:10,735 --> 00:02:12,204
Move along.

14
00:02:13,654 --> 00:02:17,196
And now we come to the next object
on our list, or I should say objects

15
00:02:17,262 --> 00:02:19,176
because there are three of them.

16
00:02:19,242 --> 00:02:23,704
Now ladies and gentlemen these can
be bought together or separately.

17
00:02:23,770 --> 00:02:27,063
Now these beautiful little musical
boxes only arrived this morning

18
00:02:27,129 --> 00:02:29,452
and I didn't intend to put them
on the auction block until later

19
00:02:29,518 --> 00:02:31,391
but I'm going to sell them now.

20
00:02:31,457 --> 00:02:34,940
So good friends, as our old
pal Mark Anthony used to say,

21
00:02:35,006 --> 00:02:38,018
"lend me your ears

22
00:02:38,084 --> 00:02:39,817
and what do you hear?"

23
00:02:39,884 --> 00:02:42,027
♪♪Right,

24
00:02:42,093 --> 00:02:46,105
the beautiful tinkle,
tinkle of a musical box.

25
00:02:46,171 --> 00:02:48,864
What a lovely trinket.
What a beautiful gift,

26
00:02:48,930 --> 00:02:50,694
created and made by loving hands.

27
00:02:50,760 --> 00:02:53,862
A thing of beauty and utility.

28
00:02:53,928 --> 00:02:56,871
I was going to start with five pounds.

29
00:02:56,937 --> 00:02:59,160
It's a bargain for five pounds.

30
00:02:59,226 --> 00:03:02,079
Do I see any hands?

31
00:03:02,145 --> 00:03:06,118
Is there a connoisseur in the house
who'll go three pounds for it?

32
00:03:06,184 --> 00:03:07,563
Two pounds?

33
00:03:08,563 --> 00:03:09,802
One pound?

34
00:03:11,692 --> 00:03:14,005
Ten shillings?

35
00:03:14,071 --> 00:03:16,714
Ten? Thank you, sir.

36
00:03:16,780 --> 00:03:17,923
Ladies and gentlemen,

37
00:03:17,989 --> 00:03:20,052
ten shillings is offered for a musical box

38
00:03:20,118 --> 00:03:23,051
you couldn't buy anywhere in
London for less than five pounds.

39
00:03:23,117 --> 00:03:25,420
It's a bit of a stealing to
let it go for ten shillings,

40
00:03:25,486 --> 00:03:26,970
like taking milk from a baby.

41
00:03:27,036 --> 00:03:28,639
All right, we start with ten shillings.

42
00:03:28,704 --> 00:03:30,139
Ten shillings, ten shillings is offered.

43
00:03:30,204 --> 00:03:31,468
Ten shillings is offered.
Ten shillings is offered.

44
00:03:31,534 --> 00:03:32,808
Does anybody want to give me one pound?

45
00:03:32,874 --> 00:03:34,477
Anybody one pound?

46
00:03:34,543 --> 00:03:36,136
Won't somebody give me a pound?

47
00:03:36,202 --> 00:03:38,055
A pound, one pound is offered, one pound.

48
00:03:38,122 --> 00:03:39,645
Ladies and gentlemen one pound.

49
00:03:39,711 --> 00:03:41,564
The offer is against you, sir.
Will you go to two pounds?

50
00:03:41,630 --> 00:03:43,933
Will you go to two pounds, sir?

51
00:03:43,999 --> 00:03:45,353
Two pounds.
Two pounds is offered.

52
00:03:45,418 --> 00:03:46,982
Two pounds offered going once,

53
00:03:47,048 --> 00:03:48,062
twice,

54
00:03:48,128 --> 00:03:50,441
third and the last call.

55
00:03:50,507 --> 00:03:53,190
Sold to the gentlemen for two pounds.

56
00:03:53,256 --> 00:03:55,149
Sorry, my dear.

57
00:03:55,215 --> 00:03:58,868
Now ladies and gentlemen comes
the opportunity to purchase

58
00:03:58,934 --> 00:04:01,407
an exact duplicate of the
beautiful little musical box

59
00:04:01,473 --> 00:04:04,446
just bought by this gentleman
for the ridiculous low price

60
00:04:04,512 --> 00:04:05,455
of two pounds.

61
00:04:05,521 --> 00:04:06,995
Now, it's exactly the same.

62
00:04:07,061 --> 00:04:08,994
Exactly the same.
Made by the same hands.

63
00:04:09,060 --> 00:04:10,993
You hear that?
Isn't that lovely.

64
00:04:11,059 --> 00:04:13,292
That tinkle, tinkle, tinkle, tinkle.

65
00:04:13,358 --> 00:04:14,752
Sounds like bow bells to me.

66
00:04:14,818 --> 00:04:16,870
You know, with little angels
pulling on the ropes.

67
00:04:16,937 --> 00:04:18,380
Who will give me two pounds for it?

68
00:04:18,446 --> 00:04:19,589
Who will start me with two pounds?

69
00:04:19,656 --> 00:04:21,709
Will anybody start me with two pounds?

70
00:04:21,774 --> 00:04:24,048
Oh come, come ladies and gentlemen,

71
00:04:24,114 --> 00:04:26,967
if you offer more enthusiasm we might
all be Scotland instead of London.

72
00:04:27,033 --> 00:04:28,756
Please buy it for me, Daddy.

73
00:04:28,822 --> 00:04:30,296
Two pounds? Certainly not.

74
00:04:30,362 --> 00:04:32,215
We all might be in Scotland.

75
00:04:32,281 --> 00:04:34,214
Besides I don't like his manner.

76
00:04:34,280 --> 00:04:35,884
One pound, ten shillings.

77
00:04:35,950 --> 00:04:37,843
One pound. One pound is asked.

78
00:04:37,909 --> 00:04:39,092
One pound? One pound is offered.

79
00:04:39,158 --> 00:04:40,762
One pound is offered.
Going, one pound.

80
00:04:40,828 --> 00:04:43,391
In advance.
Going once, going twice,

81
00:04:43,457 --> 00:04:46,270
the third and the last call.

82
00:04:46,336 --> 00:04:48,558
Sold to the lady for one pound.

83
00:04:48,625 --> 00:04:50,188
Smart bidding, my dear.

84
00:04:50,254 --> 00:04:51,268
Thank you.

85
00:04:51,334 --> 00:04:52,687
We come to the third and last

86
00:04:52,753 --> 00:04:55,276
of these beautiful little musical boxes.

87
00:04:55,342 --> 00:04:58,855
Exactly the same tinkle,
tinkle. Isn't that lovely?

88
00:04:58,921 --> 00:05:00,154
Ladies and gentlemen
I don't bring you here

89
00:05:00,220 --> 00:05:01,864
to gull you and swindle you,

90
00:05:01,930 --> 00:05:05,088
this is the exact replica of
those two I just sold before.

91
00:05:12,016 --> 00:05:13,039
We're closed.

92
00:05:13,105 --> 00:05:15,854
But this is extremely important.

93
00:05:17,974 --> 00:05:18,917
Come in, sir. Come in.

94
00:05:18,983 --> 00:05:20,577
I'm sorry to disturb you

95
00:05:20,643 --> 00:05:22,456
but I was unfortunately delayed

96
00:05:22,522 --> 00:05:24,915
from arriving in time to
bid on certain articles,

97
00:05:24,981 --> 00:05:26,914
which I was rather anxious to obtain.

98
00:05:26,980 --> 00:05:28,623
Well, perhaps they weren't sold, sir.

99
00:05:28,689 --> 00:05:30,793
We are carrying several things over.

100
00:05:30,859 --> 00:05:32,922
What might the articles be, sir?

101
00:05:32,988 --> 00:05:36,920
Three identical musical
boxes about so large.

102
00:05:36,986 --> 00:05:39,549
Oh, I'm sorry, sir, but they were sold.

103
00:05:39,615 --> 00:05:41,089
Pitty you weren't here to bid on them.

104
00:05:41,155 --> 00:05:43,558
They didn't bring anything
like their real value.

105
00:05:43,624 --> 00:05:45,847
I'm most anxious to obtain them.

106
00:05:45,913 --> 00:05:47,516
I wonder if your records would show

107
00:05:47,582 --> 00:05:49,476
who the purchases were?

108
00:05:49,542 --> 00:05:52,433
Oh, we don't usually give
out that information, sir.

109
00:05:52,500 --> 00:05:55,523
For certain, shall we say,
sentimental reasons

110
00:05:55,589 --> 00:05:58,692
I'm most anxious to get in
touch with the purchasers.

111
00:05:58,758 --> 00:06:02,401
I'd be willing to pay, shall we say,

112
00:06:02,467 --> 00:06:03,770
five pounds.

113
00:06:03,836 --> 00:06:05,439
Well for certain sentimental reasons, sir,

114
00:06:05,505 --> 00:06:07,109
we'd be very happy to oblige.

115
00:06:07,175 --> 00:06:10,108
Alfred, today's sales,
the three musical boxes.

116
00:06:10,174 --> 00:06:12,197
The musical boxes, oh.

117
00:06:12,263 --> 00:06:14,326
Ah, here we are.

118
00:06:14,392 --> 00:06:17,155
The first purchased for two pounds by
Mr. Julian Emery, 52 Portland Square.

119
00:06:17,221 --> 00:06:19,574
- Write these addresses down, Alfred.
- Yes, sir.

120
00:06:19,640 --> 00:06:20,954
Second, didn't leave any name.

121
00:06:21,020 --> 00:06:22,663
Well, how unfortunate.

122
00:06:22,729 --> 00:06:24,452
I think she's a dealer.

123
00:06:24,518 --> 00:06:25,742
You see, they don't like us to
know where the things are going.

124
00:06:25,808 --> 00:06:27,541
On account of the profits.

125
00:06:27,607 --> 00:06:30,750
You say the second purchaser,
there was a woman,

126
00:06:30,816 --> 00:06:33,039
can you give me a description of her?

127
00:06:33,105 --> 00:06:36,548
Oh, she was a young woman,
fairly tall, slender,

128
00:06:36,614 --> 00:06:39,466
a light complexion and dark hair,

129
00:06:39,532 --> 00:06:42,715
- and she was wearing a...
- A gray suit, don't you remember?

130
00:06:42,781 --> 00:06:45,384
- That's right.
- She probably runs a gift shop.

131
00:06:45,450 --> 00:06:48,383
She paid one pound.

132
00:06:48,449 --> 00:06:51,592
You say she comes here fairly frequently?

133
00:06:51,658 --> 00:06:54,931
No, I didn't say so but she does, sir.

134
00:06:54,997 --> 00:06:56,930
Likely, she'll come in on Thursday.

135
00:06:56,996 --> 00:06:59,308
We have sales on Monday's and Thursday's.

136
00:06:59,375 --> 00:07:01,648
Ah. And the third box?

137
00:07:01,714 --> 00:07:06,776
The third, oh, a Mr. William
Kilgour, 143B Hampton Way.

138
00:07:06,842 --> 00:07:08,565
For ten shillings.

139
00:07:08,631 --> 00:07:10,525
Quite a drop from two pounds.

140
00:07:10,591 --> 00:07:13,444
Mr. Kilgour was a Scotchman.

141
00:07:13,510 --> 00:07:17,322
Well, thank you.
You've been most helpful.

142
00:07:17,388 --> 00:07:18,402
Thank you, sir

143
00:07:18,468 --> 00:07:20,571
and anytime your passing drop in.

144
00:07:20,637 --> 00:07:22,530
We always have lovely things for sale.

145
00:07:22,596 --> 00:07:24,369
- Our card, sir.
- Thank you.

146
00:07:24,435 --> 00:07:26,445
I'll be back Thursday.

147
00:07:34,102 --> 00:07:37,165
Her message reached us too late.

148
00:07:37,230 --> 00:07:40,209
The musical boxes have been sold.

149
00:07:41,989 --> 00:07:44,188
Well, let's get out of here.

150
00:07:49,986 --> 00:07:52,415
Some day you'll go too far.

151
00:07:55,324 --> 00:07:58,097
Reaching for a star, you fool.

152
00:07:58,163 --> 00:08:01,015
Yet a fool may touch a star,
Colonel Cavanaugh

153
00:08:01,081 --> 00:08:03,185
if he reaches high enough.

154
00:08:03,251 --> 00:08:05,770
But not possess it as you would.

155
00:08:07,499 --> 00:08:09,982
The musical boxes they've been sold?

156
00:08:10,048 --> 00:08:11,981
What a pity for you, my dear Colonel.

157
00:08:12,047 --> 00:08:15,560
Is it my fault that the message
reached us only an hour ago?

158
00:08:15,626 --> 00:08:18,149
Is it my fault that they were sold?

159
00:08:18,215 --> 00:08:21,108
She can't hold me responsible for that.

160
00:08:21,174 --> 00:08:22,883
Hope for your sake you're right.

161
00:08:54,651 --> 00:08:56,964
"They will call upon you tonight
at a quarter till eight,"

162
00:08:57,030 --> 00:08:59,343
a gentleman it is asked to consult you

163
00:08:59,409 --> 00:09:02,302
"upon a matter of the
very deepest moment."

164
00:09:02,368 --> 00:09:04,131
Remember that letter, Holmes?

165
00:09:04,197 --> 00:09:06,550
It was written over two years ago.

166
00:09:06,616 --> 00:09:07,970
Very interesting case.

167
00:09:08,036 --> 00:09:09,969
Devilishly interesting.

168
00:09:10,035 --> 00:09:12,388
Humph, Irene Adler,

169
00:09:12,454 --> 00:09:13,848
what a striking looking woman

170
00:09:13,914 --> 00:09:15,517
from the brief glance I had of her.

171
00:09:15,583 --> 00:09:17,306
Seems only yesterday.

172
00:09:17,372 --> 00:09:19,186
What charm.

173
00:09:19,252 --> 00:09:21,985
What poise. And what a mind.

174
00:09:22,051 --> 00:09:23,274
Sharp enough and brilliant enough

175
00:09:23,340 --> 00:09:27,522
to outwit the great
Sherlock Holmes himself.

176
00:09:27,588 --> 00:09:30,032
I take it that the new issue
of the Strand Magazine is out,

177
00:09:30,097 --> 00:09:32,820
containing another of
your slightly lurid tales.

178
00:09:32,886 --> 00:09:33,900
It is indeed.

179
00:09:33,966 --> 00:09:35,659
And what do you call this one?

180
00:09:35,725 --> 00:09:39,448
I call it "A Scandal in Bohemia".
Not a bad title, huh?

181
00:09:39,514 --> 00:09:43,706
Hmm. If you must
record my exploits

182
00:09:43,772 --> 00:09:46,665
I do wish you would put less
emphasis on the melodramatic

183
00:09:46,731 --> 00:09:49,204
and more on the intellectual
issues involved.

184
00:09:49,270 --> 00:09:51,543
More on the inte... what
do you mean by that?

185
00:09:51,609 --> 00:09:56,212
Well, I do hope you've given
The Woman a soul,

186
00:09:56,278 --> 00:09:57,381
she had one you know?

187
00:09:57,447 --> 00:09:59,170
By The Woman,

188
00:09:59,236 --> 00:10:01,090
I suppose you mean Irene Adler?

189
00:10:01,156 --> 00:10:03,169
Yes,

190
00:10:03,235 --> 00:10:07,773
I shall always remember her as The woman.

191
00:10:15,330 --> 00:10:17,989
Come in.

192
00:10:20,998 --> 00:10:22,811
Stinky.

193
00:10:22,877 --> 00:10:24,351
Fatso, old boy, how are you?

194
00:10:24,417 --> 00:10:26,480
How are you, old boy?
I haven't seen you for years.

195
00:10:26,546 --> 00:10:28,519
I want you to meet my old
friend Sherlock Holmes.

196
00:10:28,585 --> 00:10:30,149
Holmes, this is Stinky.

197
00:10:30,215 --> 00:10:32,478
In other words Julian Emery.

198
00:10:32,544 --> 00:10:34,947
How do you do, Mr. Emery?
Watson's often spoken of you.

199
00:10:35,013 --> 00:10:36,316
Oh, has he?

200
00:10:36,382 --> 00:10:37,696
Yes, we were at school together.

201
00:10:37,762 --> 00:10:39,275
Yes, more years ago
than I care to remember

202
00:10:39,341 --> 00:10:41,534
but you didn't come in here
just to remind me of that.

203
00:10:41,600 --> 00:10:43,194
No, I just happened to
be in the neighborhood

204
00:10:43,260 --> 00:10:44,613
and saw your lights burning

205
00:10:44,679 --> 00:10:46,822
so I took the liberty of looking you up.

206
00:10:46,888 --> 00:10:48,492
Still writing the old mystery stuff?

207
00:10:48,558 --> 00:10:50,991
Yes. There's a new
one out this week.

208
00:10:51,057 --> 00:10:53,330
- Good, I never miss them.
- Oh good. Thanks.

209
00:10:53,396 --> 00:10:56,119
I say that bandage makes
you look very interesting.

210
00:10:56,185 --> 00:10:58,998
Still poking your nose into other
people's business as usual?

211
00:10:59,064 --> 00:11:01,247
- Who hit you?
- I haven't the foggiest notion.

212
00:11:01,313 --> 00:11:03,296
Somebody knocked me on the
head in my own living room

213
00:11:03,362 --> 00:11:07,294
then proceeded to commit the most
idiotic burglary you ever heard of.

214
00:11:07,360 --> 00:11:08,884
Fellow must have been barney as a coot.

215
00:11:08,950 --> 00:11:10,713
Barney, why?

216
00:11:10,779 --> 00:11:12,133
Come sit down, old boy.

217
00:11:12,199 --> 00:11:14,972
- Would you like a cup of tea?
- Huh?

218
00:11:15,038 --> 00:11:16,471
Oh, all right.

219
00:11:16,537 --> 00:11:18,566
I'll go and tell
Mrs. Hudson about it.

220
00:11:21,875 --> 00:11:23,968
Why did you say the robbery
was idiotic, Mr. Emery?

221
00:11:24,034 --> 00:11:25,597
Oh, simply from the fact that

222
00:11:25,663 --> 00:11:27,097
with about five thousand pounds worth

223
00:11:27,163 --> 00:11:28,806
of musical boxes in my living room

224
00:11:28,872 --> 00:11:30,726
the thief, who I caught in the act,

225
00:11:30,791 --> 00:11:33,395
made off with one that isn't
even worth five pounds.

226
00:11:33,460 --> 00:11:35,684
I gather you are a
collector of musical boxes?

227
00:11:35,750 --> 00:11:37,023
Yes, I am indeed.

228
00:11:37,089 --> 00:11:38,193
Some of them are very beautiful

229
00:11:38,259 --> 00:11:40,062
but not the one that was stolen.

230
00:11:40,128 --> 00:11:42,691
This thief evidently grabbed the
first thing that came to his hand

231
00:11:42,757 --> 00:11:45,030
when he heard me coming into the room.

232
00:11:45,096 --> 00:11:47,859
Still it's rather odd, isn't it,
that having disposed of you

233
00:11:47,925 --> 00:11:50,698
he didn't pick up something more valuable.

234
00:11:50,764 --> 00:11:52,987
Well, is there anything
unusual about the stolen box?

235
00:11:53,053 --> 00:11:54,996
No, nothing at all.

236
00:11:55,062 --> 00:11:57,575
I picked it up in the south of France

237
00:11:57,641 --> 00:11:59,165
several years ago.

238
00:11:59,231 --> 00:12:01,874
You say you have many valuable music boxes

239
00:12:01,940 --> 00:12:04,873
and yet the thief made off with one
that's isn't worth five pounds.

240
00:12:04,938 --> 00:12:07,252
Sounds like a rather
intriguing little problem.

241
00:12:07,318 --> 00:12:09,881
Yes, well I take it that he was
just an ordinary petty thief

242
00:12:09,947 --> 00:12:11,380
and didn't know the value.

243
00:12:11,446 --> 00:12:14,209
That is a possible explanation,
yet I adventure to say

244
00:12:14,275 --> 00:12:17,088
that the average petty thief has a
more extensive knowledge of the value

245
00:12:17,154 --> 00:12:19,177
of the object d'art than
the average collector.

246
00:12:19,243 --> 00:12:21,426
Well anyway, that's Scotland Yards theory

247
00:12:21,492 --> 00:12:23,256
they didn't get very excited about it.

248
00:12:23,321 --> 00:12:25,465
That's consistent anyway.

249
00:12:25,531 --> 00:12:27,924
I wonder if I might see
your collection, Mr. Emery?

250
00:12:27,990 --> 00:12:29,803
Why of course you can. Yes.

251
00:12:29,869 --> 00:12:31,182
Nothing that a collector likes more

252
00:12:31,248 --> 00:12:32,932
than showing off his trophies.

253
00:12:32,998 --> 00:12:35,681
- When would it suit you?
- No time like the present.

254
00:12:35,747 --> 00:12:36,930
Good.

255
00:12:36,996 --> 00:12:38,440
My place is just around in Pullman Square.

256
00:12:38,506 --> 00:12:40,285
- Shall we?
- Yes, right.

257
00:12:44,463 --> 00:12:46,027
Hello. Where you going?

258
00:12:46,093 --> 00:12:48,396
- Stinky hasn't had his tea yet.
- Oh, I'm sorry.

259
00:12:48,462 --> 00:12:49,985
We're going round to my place

260
00:12:50,051 --> 00:12:53,020
where I'm going to give you
something better than tea.

261
00:12:54,390 --> 00:12:56,783
Now this one was made for Louis the XV

262
00:12:56,849 --> 00:12:59,532
and is one of the very few still
in the existence from that period

263
00:12:59,598 --> 00:13:01,797
and a particularly fine specimen at that.

264
00:13:04,846 --> 00:13:06,699
Charming isn't it?

265
00:13:06,765 --> 00:13:08,464
Quite.

266
00:13:09,724 --> 00:13:11,167
They all sound to me like a lot of mice

267
00:13:11,233 --> 00:13:13,336
running about on a tin roof.

268
00:13:13,402 --> 00:13:15,666
I'm afraid you have no ear
for music, Watson.

269
00:13:15,732 --> 00:13:18,205
Give me a good old band
playing a rousing march,

270
00:13:18,271 --> 00:13:20,640
you have all your silly
little tweet tweets.

271
00:13:26,447 --> 00:13:28,926
Oh, that's another one of them.

272
00:13:31,496 --> 00:13:33,055
Good gracious me.

273
00:13:41,792 --> 00:13:44,820
Stupid thing, singing rabbit, huh.

274
00:13:46,710 --> 00:13:48,563
What would you say offhand is the
value of a box like that, Mr. Emery?

275
00:13:48,629 --> 00:13:51,442
Well, it's hard to say offhand
but I think it would bring

276
00:13:51,508 --> 00:13:53,611
about five or six hundred pounds today.

277
00:13:53,677 --> 00:13:55,230
It's the gem of my collection.

278
00:13:55,296 --> 00:13:57,570
Yet a thief, who steals an
oddity like a musical box,

279
00:13:57,636 --> 00:13:59,489
passes up one worth five hundred pounds

280
00:13:59,555 --> 00:14:01,948
for one of almost no value at all.

281
00:14:02,014 --> 00:14:04,867
Odd, very odd.

282
00:14:04,933 --> 00:14:06,786
What was the stolen box like,
Mr. Emery?

283
00:14:06,852 --> 00:14:10,745
Oh, just plain wooden box about so big.

284
00:14:10,811 --> 00:14:14,783
As a matter fact, I have one over
here almost exactly like it.

285
00:14:14,849 --> 00:14:18,122
I picked this up yesterday at an
auction room in Knightsbridge,

286
00:14:18,188 --> 00:14:20,001
paid only two pounds for it.

287
00:14:20,067 --> 00:14:21,750
Of course, I wouldn't have ordinarily

288
00:14:21,816 --> 00:14:25,879
add one like this to my collection
but the tune intrigued me.

289
00:14:25,945 --> 00:14:29,244
I'd never heard it before.

290
00:14:45,417 --> 00:14:47,471
You have a remarkable
ear for music, Holmes.

291
00:14:47,537 --> 00:14:49,680
- Rather an unusual melody.
- Sit down, will you.

292
00:14:49,746 --> 00:14:52,099
Thanks.

293
00:14:52,165 --> 00:14:55,108
You say you bought that box
at an auction hall yesterday?

294
00:14:55,174 --> 00:14:58,526
Yes. The Gaylord Auction
Rooms in Knightsbridge,

295
00:14:58,592 --> 00:15:00,526
run by old... What's his name?

296
00:15:00,592 --> 00:15:01,815
Crabtree.

297
00:15:01,881 --> 00:15:03,025
That's the man.

298
00:15:03,091 --> 00:15:04,564
At what time was the robbery committed?

299
00:15:04,630 --> 00:15:07,323
Oh, about three o'clock this morning.

300
00:15:07,389 --> 00:15:08,822
You know, Mr. Emery

301
00:15:08,888 --> 00:15:11,571
that box and the robbery
might well be cause and effect,

302
00:15:11,637 --> 00:15:13,861
especially since you say
that the stolen box

303
00:15:13,926 --> 00:15:16,410
outwardly resembles this one a great deal

304
00:15:16,476 --> 00:15:20,078
and Scotland Yard was not
particularly interested, eh?

305
00:15:20,144 --> 00:15:22,497
Oh yes, but I wouldn't
blame them for that,

306
00:15:22,563 --> 00:15:25,326
especially as I told them I was
quite unable to describe the thief,

307
00:15:25,392 --> 00:15:28,545
except, of course, for the fact
that it was definitely a man.

308
00:15:28,611 --> 00:15:29,744
All you remember is that who came in here

309
00:15:29,810 --> 00:15:30,794
and someone struck you on the head.

310
00:15:30,860 --> 00:15:32,623
Yes and the next thing I knew

311
00:15:32,689 --> 00:15:34,583
my man was trying to revive me.

312
00:15:34,649 --> 00:15:36,752
It might be wise for you to put that
box away somewhere and lock it up.

313
00:15:36,818 --> 00:15:38,501
Oh, I don't think that's necessary.

314
00:15:38,567 --> 00:15:40,340
Besides, everything's insured.

315
00:15:40,406 --> 00:15:43,379
Well, at least of any further
attempts at robbery are made

316
00:15:43,445 --> 00:15:45,678
I'd suggest that you call the police

317
00:15:45,744 --> 00:15:47,428
rather than running into
any personal danger.

318
00:15:47,494 --> 00:15:49,847
Oh come, Holmes aren't you
being a bit of an alarmist?

319
00:15:49,913 --> 00:15:50,886
Possibly.

320
00:15:50,952 --> 00:15:52,726
I must agree with old Stinky.

321
00:15:52,792 --> 00:15:55,265
Seems to me you are making rather
a mountain out of a mole skin.

322
00:15:55,331 --> 00:15:56,724
Molehill is the word, old boy

323
00:15:56,790 --> 00:15:58,813
and it's time you were in bed.

324
00:15:58,879 --> 00:16:00,603
Thanks so much for letting
us see your collection.

325
00:16:00,669 --> 00:16:02,638
It's been grand meeting you.

326
00:16:04,417 --> 00:16:07,190
Holmes, I can't understand
why you were so mysterious.

327
00:16:07,256 --> 00:16:10,109
Seems to me the petty thief explanation
was the only sensible one.

328
00:16:10,175 --> 00:16:11,818
- Really?
- Yes, I can't see how you can believe

329
00:16:11,884 --> 00:16:13,148
it was anything else.

330
00:16:13,214 --> 00:16:14,697
I didn't say I believed
it to be anything else.

331
00:16:14,763 --> 00:16:17,366
The petty thief theory is
the obvious one I grant you.

332
00:16:17,432 --> 00:16:19,985
However, it's often a mistaken
to accept something that's true

333
00:16:20,051 --> 00:16:22,244
merely because it's obvious.

334
00:16:22,310 --> 00:16:24,404
The truth is only arrived at

335
00:16:24,470 --> 00:16:28,452
by the pain staking process
of eliminating the untrue.

336
00:16:28,518 --> 00:16:30,581
We are not able to do that in this case

337
00:16:30,647 --> 00:16:32,001
without further data.

338
00:16:32,067 --> 00:16:33,790
Rubbish. You're pulling my leg.

339
00:16:33,856 --> 00:16:35,539
You're trying to turn a

340
00:16:35,605 --> 00:16:38,668
cut on the head and a robbery
into an international plot.

341
00:16:38,734 --> 00:16:39,748
No I'm not.

342
00:16:39,814 --> 00:16:41,127
I just hope that your friend Stinky

343
00:16:41,193 --> 00:16:43,087
is a little more cautious in the future,

344
00:16:43,153 --> 00:16:44,852
just in case.

345
00:17:09,292 --> 00:17:11,685
Hello. Yeah.

346
00:17:11,752 --> 00:17:13,395
Julian Emery here.

347
00:17:13,461 --> 00:17:15,773
Who?

348
00:17:15,839 --> 00:17:19,233
Why of course I remember
you, Mrs. Courtney.

349
00:17:19,299 --> 00:17:21,862
Yes. Yes, you are the
one bright spot

350
00:17:21,928 --> 00:17:25,780
at that appallingly dull
affair of Lady Sanfords.

351
00:17:25,846 --> 00:17:27,030
Huh?

352
00:17:27,096 --> 00:17:29,369
Of course it isn't to late to come around.

353
00:17:29,435 --> 00:17:32,908
Yes, I shall be delighted
to give you a drink.

354
00:17:32,974 --> 00:17:34,447
I tell you what come straight up

355
00:17:34,513 --> 00:17:37,206
and I'll leave the door unlatched.

356
00:17:37,272 --> 00:17:39,285
All right. Fifteen minutes?

357
00:17:39,351 --> 00:17:41,084
Good.

358
00:17:41,150 --> 00:17:43,294
I shall be counting each moment.

359
00:17:43,360 --> 00:17:46,922
No. No. No, I mean that, really.

360
00:17:46,988 --> 00:17:48,678
Right. Goodbye.

361
00:18:06,871 --> 00:18:08,434
Boo!

362
00:18:08,500 --> 00:18:10,053
Oh, you startled me.

363
00:18:10,119 --> 00:18:11,763
- Did I?
- Yes.

364
00:18:11,829 --> 00:18:13,852
Must be the pixie in me.

365
00:18:13,918 --> 00:18:15,981
I know I shouldn't have called you so late

366
00:18:16,047 --> 00:18:18,350
but I was at a party
just around the corner

367
00:18:18,416 --> 00:18:19,690
and I remembered your invitation

368
00:18:19,756 --> 00:18:21,649
to see your collection of musical boxes.

369
00:18:21,715 --> 00:18:23,268
My dear, Mrs. Courtney,

370
00:18:23,334 --> 00:18:26,317
pleasure is all the greater
for being so unexpected.

371
00:18:26,383 --> 00:18:28,696
- My friends call me Hilda.
- Thanks.

372
00:18:28,762 --> 00:18:30,366
Mine call me Stinky.

373
00:18:30,432 --> 00:18:32,115
Stinky? How quaint.

374
00:18:32,181 --> 00:18:35,324
Oh, what a perfectly wonderful
collection of musical boxes.

375
00:18:35,390 --> 00:18:36,743
You know, when you told
me you had a collection

376
00:18:36,809 --> 00:18:39,532
- I had no idea that it was so attractive.
- Yes.

377
00:18:39,598 --> 00:18:41,661
They appeal to the ear

378
00:18:41,727 --> 00:18:44,290
as well as to the eye.

379
00:18:44,356 --> 00:18:46,829
Oh, what a plain little one.

380
00:18:46,895 --> 00:18:49,708
Why it looks just like a country
cousin Amid all this grandeur.

381
00:18:49,774 --> 00:18:52,877
Now, now, now you mustn't
underestimate the country cousin.

382
00:18:52,943 --> 00:18:54,916
Only last night a burglar broke in here

383
00:18:54,982 --> 00:18:56,456
and with all these to chose from

384
00:18:56,522 --> 00:18:58,165
- went off with one very much like it.
- Really?

385
00:18:58,231 --> 00:19:00,544
Yes, I don't mind the loss the box so much

386
00:19:00,610 --> 00:19:02,383
but I do resent this crack on the skull.

387
00:19:02,449 --> 00:19:03,923
But it makes you look so interesting.

388
00:19:03,989 --> 00:19:05,962
- Do you think so?
- Uh-huh.

389
00:19:06,028 --> 00:19:07,971
- That's funny, that's what old fatso said.
- Fatso?

390
00:19:08,037 --> 00:19:09,841
I mean Doctor Watson.

391
00:19:09,907 --> 00:19:13,099
He was here this evening
with a friend, a Mr. Holmes.

392
00:19:13,165 --> 00:19:14,889
He's interested in my collection too.

393
00:19:14,955 --> 00:19:16,178
Sherlock Holmes?

394
00:19:16,244 --> 00:19:17,678
Yes. Do you know him?

395
00:19:17,744 --> 00:19:19,307
I've heard of him.

396
00:19:19,373 --> 00:19:23,266
Yes, he seems to think
I'm in some sort of danger.

397
00:19:23,331 --> 00:19:26,394
What a haunting tune. It takes
me right back to my childhood.

398
00:19:26,460 --> 00:19:28,563
Really?

399
00:19:28,629 --> 00:19:30,273
You know it's odd that you should be
interested in that particular musical box.

400
00:19:30,339 --> 00:19:33,772
Odd, why?
Cause Mr. Holmes is also interested in it.

401
00:19:33,837 --> 00:19:36,820
He may have been more interested
in the tune than in the box.

402
00:19:36,886 --> 00:19:38,490
My dear, yes, that's right.

403
00:19:38,556 --> 00:19:40,029
I remember now.

404
00:19:40,095 --> 00:19:42,278
He whistled it note for note
having heard it only once.

405
00:19:42,344 --> 00:19:45,537
Really? He must be
a remarkable man.

406
00:19:45,603 --> 00:19:47,746
Bit of an alarmist if you ask me.

407
00:19:47,812 --> 00:19:49,326
Don't you believe in warnings?

408
00:19:49,392 --> 00:19:50,785
Of course not.

409
00:19:50,851 --> 00:19:52,784
Who'd want a box like that?

410
00:19:52,850 --> 00:19:53,954
I would.

411
00:19:54,020 --> 00:19:55,543
You're not serious?

412
00:19:55,609 --> 00:19:57,203
Oh, but I am.

413
00:19:57,269 --> 00:19:59,712
Well, you put me at a
very awkward position.

414
00:19:59,778 --> 00:20:01,331
I'm a collector you know

415
00:20:01,397 --> 00:20:03,630
and a collector buys but never sells.

416
00:20:03,696 --> 00:20:07,419
But if the price were high enough.

417
00:20:07,485 --> 00:20:09,258
The price has nothing to do with it.

418
00:20:09,324 --> 00:20:12,837
It's the principle of the thing.

419
00:20:12,903 --> 00:20:15,466
Yes, well we haven't had our drink.

420
00:20:15,532 --> 00:20:19,054
No thanks, I must be getting along.

421
00:20:19,120 --> 00:20:22,329
- Must you really?
- I'm afraid so.

422
00:20:23,539 --> 00:20:25,722
You're not walking out on me are you?

423
00:20:25,788 --> 00:20:30,140
My reputation, Stinky.

424
00:20:30,206 --> 00:20:32,939
I say, you know you are
an attractive woman.

425
00:20:33,005 --> 00:20:34,244
Thanks.

426
00:20:40,962 --> 00:20:44,065
You fool.
I told you to wait outside.

427
00:20:44,131 --> 00:20:46,324
What did you have to kill him for?

428
00:20:46,390 --> 00:20:48,113
All I had to do was walk out with this.

429
00:20:48,179 --> 00:20:50,952
- He held you in his arms.
- Don't touch him.

430
00:20:51,018 --> 00:20:53,621
Don't touch anything.
Now get out!

431
00:20:53,687 --> 00:20:56,280
- I'm sorry.
- You're sorry?

432
00:20:56,346 --> 00:20:59,249
What about me? This is murder.

433
00:20:59,315 --> 00:21:01,078
What about Scotland Yard?

434
00:21:01,144 --> 00:21:03,497
What about Sherlock Holmes?

435
00:21:03,563 --> 00:21:05,672
Now get out!

436
00:21:32,412 --> 00:21:34,482
Did you get it?

437
00:21:36,291 --> 00:21:37,684
Good.

438
00:21:37,750 --> 00:21:40,733
Did you have any trouble with him?

439
00:21:40,799 --> 00:21:42,908
Just a matter of murder.

440
00:21:46,677 --> 00:21:48,900
- Ah, Mr. Holmes.
- Hopkins.

441
00:21:48,966 --> 00:21:50,489
Thanks for coming so promptly.

442
00:21:50,555 --> 00:21:53,568
Inspector Lestrade suggested
that I call through to you.

443
00:21:53,634 --> 00:21:56,987
Mr. Emery was a client of
Mr. Holmes, Inspector. Indeed.

444
00:21:57,053 --> 00:21:58,986
You didn't mention that when
I telephoned you, Mr. Holmes.

445
00:21:59,052 --> 00:22:00,995
Well not exactly a client, Inspector.

446
00:22:01,061 --> 00:22:03,664
- Sergeant Thompson?
- He was killed between the hours of eleven

447
00:22:03,730 --> 00:22:06,569
and two o'clock this
morning, Mr. Holmes.

448
00:22:08,229 --> 00:22:09,452
Must have been someone he knew.

449
00:22:09,518 --> 00:22:12,251
Someone of whom he had no suspicion.

450
00:22:12,317 --> 00:22:14,000
Poor old Stinky.

451
00:22:14,066 --> 00:22:16,669
It's all my fault.
I should have prevented this.

452
00:22:16,735 --> 00:22:20,258
Well, it's no time to start
talking about that now, Doctor.

453
00:22:20,324 --> 00:22:22,047
Apparently, it's gone.

454
00:22:22,113 --> 00:22:24,047
That's the second attempt
on the musical box

455
00:22:24,113 --> 00:22:25,836
that Emery bought at the auction sale

456
00:22:25,902 --> 00:22:27,635
and this time it was successful.

457
00:22:27,701 --> 00:22:29,425
But that box is only worth two pounds.

458
00:22:29,491 --> 00:22:31,674
It's worth a man's life, Watson.

459
00:22:31,740 --> 00:22:33,473
I think we'd better
pay a visit to Gaylord's

460
00:22:33,539 --> 00:22:35,092
Auction Room and that fellow Crabtree.

461
00:22:35,158 --> 00:22:36,472
Inspector may I suggest

462
00:22:36,538 --> 00:22:38,261
that you make a complete
search of this flat

463
00:22:38,327 --> 00:22:41,980
for a small plain musical
box about that size.

464
00:22:42,046 --> 00:22:44,015
Thank you. Come on, Watson.

465
00:22:45,754 --> 00:22:48,357
You say the first box
went to Mr. Julian Emery,

466
00:22:48,423 --> 00:22:51,686
the second, Mr. Kilgour,
143B Hampton Way,

467
00:22:51,752 --> 00:22:53,565
and the third to the
unidentified young lady

468
00:22:53,631 --> 00:22:55,815
who presumably has a shop
and lives near Golders Green?

469
00:22:55,881 --> 00:22:57,154
That's right Mr. Holmes.

470
00:22:57,220 --> 00:22:59,573
Isn't it rather strange,
Mr. Crabtree,

471
00:22:59,639 --> 00:23:02,692
that you've had three identical musical
boxes, all playing the same tune?

472
00:23:02,758 --> 00:23:04,611
- Where did they come from?
- Dartmoor Prison.

473
00:23:04,677 --> 00:23:07,700
Dartmoor? We get a regular
shipment from there every month.

474
00:23:07,766 --> 00:23:09,079
The inmates manufacture them.

475
00:23:09,145 --> 00:23:10,409
Well, they make all kinds
of things you know?

476
00:23:10,475 --> 00:23:12,078
Pipe racks, wastepaper baskets,

477
00:23:12,144 --> 00:23:14,537
- musical boxes.
- Did you happen to notice

478
00:23:14,603 --> 00:23:17,666
if anyone showed any particular
interest during the auction

479
00:23:17,732 --> 00:23:21,625
in the purchases of these three boxes?

480
00:23:21,691 --> 00:23:23,374
Oh, come now, Mr. Crabtree,

481
00:23:23,440 --> 00:23:25,793
this is very literally a
matter of life and death.

482
00:23:25,859 --> 00:23:28,172
Well, since you put it
that way, Mr. Holmes,

483
00:23:28,238 --> 00:23:30,461
there was a gentleman came in here
about an hour after closing time.

484
00:23:30,527 --> 00:23:34,420
And he was in an awful state, he was,

485
00:23:34,486 --> 00:23:36,509
he gave me five pounds to tell
him where the boxes had gone.

486
00:23:36,575 --> 00:23:38,508
He said they had sentimental
value for him, sir.

487
00:23:38,574 --> 00:23:40,388
Expensive sentiment.

488
00:23:40,454 --> 00:23:41,637
Can you describe him?

489
00:23:41,703 --> 00:23:43,176
Well he was tall, distinguished looking

490
00:23:43,242 --> 00:23:45,096
and he had gray hair and a mustache.

491
00:23:45,162 --> 00:23:46,385
He was quite a gentleman, sir.

492
00:23:46,451 --> 00:23:47,935
And what was his reaction

493
00:23:48,001 --> 00:23:49,724
when you were unable to supply him

494
00:23:49,790 --> 00:23:51,603
with the address of the young
lady who owned the shop?

495
00:23:51,669 --> 00:23:54,102
I told him that the young lady
usually come back on Thursday.

496
00:23:54,168 --> 00:23:56,811
He said he'd come back on
Thursday and that's tomorrow.

497
00:23:56,877 --> 00:23:59,560
Thank you Mr. Crabtree, you've
been very helpful. Thank you.

498
00:23:59,626 --> 00:24:01,150
Come along, Watson.

499
00:24:01,216 --> 00:24:03,359
- Where we going now, Holmes?
- The home of Mr. Kilgour,

500
00:24:03,425 --> 00:24:05,214
the man who bought the third box.

501
00:24:11,472 --> 00:24:13,325
But hang it all, Holmes,

502
00:24:13,391 --> 00:24:15,404
how do you know those other two
musical boxes are of any importance?

503
00:24:15,470 --> 00:24:16,904
I don't, but I certainly have no intention

504
00:24:16,970 --> 00:24:19,779
of waiting till the owners
are murdered to find out.

505
00:24:21,688 --> 00:24:23,081
No one at home.

506
00:24:23,147 --> 00:24:25,370
I hope that's the explanation.

507
00:24:25,436 --> 00:24:27,596
Well, have a look through this window.

508
00:24:32,774 --> 00:24:35,796
Doesn't seem to be anyone there.

509
00:24:35,862 --> 00:24:39,675
Whole place seems deserted
as far as I can see.

510
00:24:39,741 --> 00:24:42,214
- Yes?
- Mr. and Mrs. Kilgour at home?

511
00:24:42,280 --> 00:24:43,843
- No.
- When do you expect them?

512
00:24:43,909 --> 00:24:45,843
Oh, in an hour or so.

513
00:24:45,909 --> 00:24:47,512
There's no use you're hanging about.

514
00:24:47,578 --> 00:24:49,141
They don't buy nothing from peddlers.

515
00:24:49,207 --> 00:24:50,431
Peddlers?

516
00:24:50,497 --> 00:24:52,470
My good woman this is
Mr. Sherlock Holmes.

517
00:24:52,536 --> 00:24:54,429
Sherlock Holmes? Oh, go on.

518
00:24:54,495 --> 00:24:56,479
Do you mind if we come in and wait?

519
00:24:56,545 --> 00:24:57,848
My business is rather urgent.

520
00:24:57,914 --> 00:25:00,807
Well, I've got to go out to do my shopping

521
00:25:00,873 --> 00:25:02,436
and I don't know if Mrs. Kilgour

522
00:25:02,502 --> 00:25:04,436
would like any strangers nosing about.

523
00:25:04,502 --> 00:25:06,025
Quite all right, I assure you.

524
00:25:06,091 --> 00:25:07,524
Well, I've got to be off.

525
00:25:07,590 --> 00:25:11,023
You two wait in the parlor
and no smoking either.

526
00:25:11,089 --> 00:25:15,991
Mrs. Kilgour says it
smells up the house.

527
00:25:16,057 --> 00:25:18,616
- Funny old girl, Holmes.
- Hmm.

528
00:25:36,069 --> 00:25:38,043
- Park Lane.
- Park Lane?

529
00:25:38,109 --> 00:25:40,212
And what would the likes of
you be doing in Park Lane?

530
00:25:40,278 --> 00:25:42,171
Now don't worry about the fare, ducky.

531
00:25:42,237 --> 00:25:45,266
If ya knows how to get
to Park Lane, now off it.

532
00:25:50,364 --> 00:25:52,427
You know, Holmes, I've been thinking.

533
00:25:52,493 --> 00:25:53,507
There must have been something hidden

534
00:25:53,573 --> 00:25:56,266
in that box of old Stinky's.

535
00:25:56,332 --> 00:25:59,634
Stolen jewelry possibly.

536
00:25:59,700 --> 00:26:02,090
- What's up Holmes?
- Listen.

537
00:26:04,249 --> 00:26:06,958
Well, it's just the steam
in the water pipes.

538
00:26:12,756 --> 00:26:14,125
Watson!

539
00:26:16,294 --> 00:26:17,904
Great Scott!

540
00:26:19,303 --> 00:26:21,772
Come along, Holmes,
get her on the chair here.

541
00:26:22,592 --> 00:26:25,301
Shh. It's all right, my dear.

542
00:26:26,350 --> 00:26:29,573
There, there, there.
Now don't worry.

543
00:26:29,639 --> 00:26:31,572
It's all over.

544
00:26:31,638 --> 00:26:33,871
There you are, dear.
Don't cry anymore.

545
00:26:33,937 --> 00:26:36,660
She tied me up and
shut me in the cupboard.

546
00:26:36,726 --> 00:26:38,500
I know, I know.

547
00:26:38,566 --> 00:26:40,419
She won't come back.

548
00:26:40,485 --> 00:26:42,538
Did you show her your new musical box?

549
00:26:42,604 --> 00:26:45,167
Yes. She said she
wanted to hear it play

550
00:26:45,233 --> 00:26:47,858
and as soon as I showed it
to her she grabbed a hold...

551
00:26:47,924 --> 00:26:48,916
I know. I know now.

552
00:26:48,982 --> 00:26:51,175
Now don't worry, we'll buy
you a new musical box.

553
00:26:51,241 --> 00:26:53,424
Yes, my dear, the best one in London.

554
00:26:53,490 --> 00:26:55,593
Watson.

555
00:26:55,659 --> 00:26:57,762
Oh, what a fool, what a fool I've been.

556
00:26:57,828 --> 00:26:59,092
What do you mean, Holmes?

557
00:26:59,158 --> 00:27:00,301
She took the musical box out of this house

558
00:27:00,367 --> 00:27:01,881
in that market basket

559
00:27:01,947 --> 00:27:03,640
right under our very noses.

560
00:27:03,706 --> 00:27:06,809
Why would the Kilgour charwoman
want to take the music box?

561
00:27:06,875 --> 00:27:08,388
She isn't the Kilgour charwoman

562
00:27:08,454 --> 00:27:10,268
she's a consummate actress.

563
00:27:10,334 --> 00:27:12,687
An extremely clever, unscrupulous
woman who will stop at nothing.

564
00:27:12,753 --> 00:27:14,056
Take care of the child,
will you, old fellow,

565
00:27:14,122 --> 00:27:15,815
till her parents get back.

566
00:27:15,881 --> 00:27:18,105
- Explain everything to them.
- Of course I will.

567
00:27:18,171 --> 00:27:19,984
But Holmes, where are you going?

568
00:27:20,050 --> 00:27:21,773
Somewhere, somehow

569
00:27:21,839 --> 00:27:24,112
I must get to the young lady who
bought that third musical box

570
00:27:24,178 --> 00:27:25,822
before our opponents find her.

571
00:27:25,888 --> 00:27:28,317
I only hope that I won't be too late.

572
00:27:33,635 --> 00:27:36,867
Now, now, now, darling
you mustn't cry anymore.

573
00:27:36,933 --> 00:27:38,197
Cheer up.

574
00:27:38,263 --> 00:27:40,366
Would you... would you
like to hear old uncle

575
00:27:40,432 --> 00:27:42,861
make a noise like a duck?

576
00:27:51,858 --> 00:27:54,107
Oh, sorry. Huh.

577
00:28:19,037 --> 00:28:21,021
Now, ladies and gentlemen
how much am I offered

578
00:28:21,087 --> 00:28:25,149
for this beautiful laced
Dresden china figurine?

579
00:28:25,215 --> 00:28:27,018
A lady of the French court.

580
00:28:27,084 --> 00:28:30,227
Now this is the genuine article.

581
00:28:30,293 --> 00:28:32,316
What a beautiful ornament
for your mantelpiece

582
00:28:32,382 --> 00:28:34,985
as a centerpiece on the dining room table.

583
00:28:35,051 --> 00:28:37,065
Now will somebody start me for ten pounds?

584
00:28:37,130 --> 00:28:39,074
Will somebody start me for ten pounds?

585
00:28:39,140 --> 00:28:40,823
Eight pounds?

586
00:28:40,889 --> 00:28:42,283
Seven pounds?

587
00:28:42,349 --> 00:28:43,612
All right five.

588
00:28:43,678 --> 00:28:44,572
Five pounds is offered.
Five pounds is offered.

589
00:28:44,638 --> 00:28:45,621
Five pounds is offered.

590
00:28:45,687 --> 00:28:46,911
Five pounds ten.

591
00:28:46,977 --> 00:28:50,329
Five pounds fifteen, five pounds fifteen.

592
00:28:50,395 --> 00:28:52,289
Six pounds is offered.
Six pounds, six pounds,

593
00:28:52,355 --> 00:28:53,998
going once, going twice,

594
00:28:54,064 --> 00:28:55,787
the third and the last call
we're all done.

595
00:28:55,853 --> 00:28:58,372
Sold to the lady from
Trikland for six pounds.

596
00:28:59,982 --> 00:29:03,544
Next we have a real museum
piece ladies and gentlemen.

597
00:29:03,610 --> 00:29:06,173
A fine nineteenth century doll.

598
00:29:06,239 --> 00:29:08,922
The costume, an exact replica
of the holiday clothes worn

599
00:29:08,988 --> 00:29:11,092
by the Hungarian peasant women.

600
00:29:11,158 --> 00:29:13,261
Now ladies and gentlemen,

601
00:29:13,327 --> 00:29:16,340
an article like this would cost him fifteen
to twenty pounds in a west end shop.

602
00:29:16,406 --> 00:29:18,219
I'm not going to ask
for anything like that.

603
00:29:18,285 --> 00:29:19,638
Who will give me two pounds for it?

604
00:29:19,704 --> 00:29:21,218
Two pounds, anybody offer me two pounds?

605
00:29:21,284 --> 00:29:23,347
Two pounds, for the Hungarian, two...

606
00:29:23,413 --> 00:29:24,436
One pound?

607
00:29:24,502 --> 00:29:25,686
Will anybody give me one pound?

608
00:29:25,752 --> 00:29:27,605
Anybody offer me one pound for the doll?

609
00:29:27,671 --> 00:29:30,264
One pound is offered, ladies and gentlemen.
One pound is offered.

610
00:29:30,330 --> 00:29:33,273
Now I'm not going to waste
your valuable time or mine

611
00:29:33,339 --> 00:29:36,062
in trying to get one half of what
this beautiful doll is worth.

612
00:29:36,128 --> 00:29:39,521
If the young lady can steal it for
one pound that's her good fortune.

613
00:29:39,587 --> 00:29:41,230
So, it's going once, it's going twice,

614
00:29:41,296 --> 00:29:43,819
the third and last call, anymore?

615
00:29:43,885 --> 00:29:46,778
Sold to the young lady for one pound.

616
00:29:46,844 --> 00:29:48,817
Now, ladies and gentlemen
may I draw your attention

617
00:29:48,883 --> 00:29:50,786
to something, which may be,
a great surprise to you,

618
00:29:50,852 --> 00:29:52,576
worthy of any collection.

619
00:29:52,642 --> 00:29:55,495
The only other one like it
is in the British museum.

620
00:29:55,561 --> 00:29:58,623
It's a Ming vase of the seventh dynasty.

621
00:29:58,689 --> 00:30:01,702
This vase lay in a large collection

622
00:30:01,768 --> 00:30:04,751
somewhere outside Rome for over
two centuries I understand.

623
00:30:04,817 --> 00:30:06,171
It was just discovered there

624
00:30:06,237 --> 00:30:08,500
by the noted antiquarian
Sir Andrew Copperstone.

625
00:30:08,566 --> 00:30:10,799
Now, some of you may remember
Sir Andrew Copperstone.

626
00:30:10,865 --> 00:30:12,668
Besides being a world traveled antiquarian

627
00:30:12,734 --> 00:30:14,933
he's also a gentleman writer.

628
00:30:19,362 --> 00:30:22,384
The girl with the parcel
in her hands, that's her.

629
00:30:22,450 --> 00:30:24,134
Are you sure that's the girl?

630
00:30:24,200 --> 00:30:27,093
She fits perfectly the
auctioneer's description.

631
00:30:27,159 --> 00:30:29,228
Follow her, Hamid.

632
00:31:05,894 --> 00:31:07,537
It's lovely, dear.

633
00:31:07,603 --> 00:31:08,957
And only one pound.

634
00:31:09,023 --> 00:31:10,496
We can get at least three for it.

635
00:31:10,562 --> 00:31:12,995
Easily. I'll go make some tea.

636
00:31:13,061 --> 00:31:14,990
- I could do with a cup.
- Right.

637
00:31:19,399 --> 00:31:21,252
- Good afternoon.
- Good afternoon.

638
00:31:21,318 --> 00:31:22,671
I'm looking for a birthday gift

639
00:31:22,737 --> 00:31:24,921
for a seven-year-old girl.
What would you suggest?

640
00:31:24,987 --> 00:31:26,590
We have some lovely dolls.

641
00:31:26,656 --> 00:31:29,259
- Now this Hungarian...
- I think she has enough dolls already.

642
00:31:29,325 --> 00:31:30,798
Books are always welcome.

643
00:31:30,864 --> 00:31:33,007
Well, I'm looking for
something a little different.

644
00:31:33,073 --> 00:31:35,517
Well, that's rather cute, what is it?

645
00:31:35,583 --> 00:31:37,266
Oh, that's a musical box.

646
00:31:37,332 --> 00:31:39,265
Children always love them

647
00:31:39,331 --> 00:31:42,224
and this is an exceptionally nice one.

648
00:31:42,290 --> 00:31:43,709
It plays many tunes.

649
00:31:50,297 --> 00:31:52,060
- Have you any others?
- Yes.

650
00:31:52,126 --> 00:31:53,940
If you'll just step this way.

651
00:31:54,005 --> 00:31:55,885
I have only two left.

652
00:32:00,263 --> 00:32:01,683
How nice.

653
00:32:06,471 --> 00:32:08,034
Are you sure this is all you have?

654
00:32:08,100 --> 00:32:09,244
I'm sorry

655
00:32:09,310 --> 00:32:11,073
they're rather hard to find, you know.

656
00:32:11,139 --> 00:32:12,992
That's our entire allotment.

657
00:32:13,058 --> 00:32:16,121
I did have one other but I sold
it earlier this afternoon.

658
00:32:16,187 --> 00:32:17,620
But it was only a plain wooden one.

659
00:32:17,686 --> 00:32:19,790
It wouldn't have been a
very nice gift for a child.

660
00:32:19,856 --> 00:32:21,499
Really?

661
00:32:21,565 --> 00:32:24,588
Do you happen to know
who the purchaser was?

662
00:32:24,654 --> 00:32:27,167
Why yes, he left his card

663
00:32:27,233 --> 00:32:30,312
just in case anyone
should inquire for him.

664
00:32:36,779 --> 00:32:38,529
How interesting.

665
00:32:40,788 --> 00:32:43,391
I'm sorry but I'm afraid I'll
have to look a bit further.

666
00:32:43,457 --> 00:32:45,930
Thank you anyway.

667
00:32:45,996 --> 00:32:48,335
Good afternoon. Thank you.

668
00:33:12,845 --> 00:33:14,455
Cabbie.

669
00:33:17,224 --> 00:33:19,577
- Follow that cab.
- Here now, what?

670
00:33:19,643 --> 00:33:22,122
- Scotland Yard.
- Hop in.

671
00:33:29,149 --> 00:33:32,422
Sherlock Holmes, I might have known.

672
00:33:32,488 --> 00:33:35,131
We thought we were the hunters

673
00:33:35,197 --> 00:33:37,300
instead of which we're the hunted.

674
00:33:37,366 --> 00:33:40,839
We've been fooled. We played
right into his hands.

675
00:33:40,905 --> 00:33:44,387
Of course, he's had us followed.

676
00:33:44,453 --> 00:33:46,387
Don't look.

677
00:33:46,453 --> 00:33:49,202
The man in front of the toyshop.

678
00:33:50,951 --> 00:33:55,489
Hamid, turn sharp right at the
next corner and again at the next.

679
00:34:01,797 --> 00:34:03,730
No photograph of her, commissioner,

680
00:34:03,796 --> 00:34:05,060
as I expected.

681
00:34:05,126 --> 00:34:06,729
She's not a known criminal.

682
00:34:06,795 --> 00:34:08,898
But how are you expect to
know her if you do find her?

683
00:34:08,964 --> 00:34:11,487
After all she was disguised
as a charwoman.

684
00:34:11,553 --> 00:34:13,275
Don't worry, old fellow

685
00:34:13,342 --> 00:34:15,485
If I ever see her again
I'll recognize her.

686
00:34:15,552 --> 00:34:17,905
Well, it won't be long till
we know who they are

687
00:34:17,971 --> 00:34:19,494
and from where they operate.

688
00:34:19,560 --> 00:34:20,824
Who's covering them?

689
00:34:20,889 --> 00:34:22,572
Sergeant Thompson is following them, sir.

690
00:34:22,639 --> 00:34:24,661
They won't get away from
him, he's a good man.

691
00:34:24,728 --> 00:34:27,741
He could have arrested them at Kibbutz's
Toy Shop if we had any proof.

692
00:34:27,806 --> 00:34:30,040
But we know that they killed Emery.

693
00:34:30,106 --> 00:34:32,895
Proof, my dear fellow, we must have proof.

694
00:34:34,734 --> 00:34:37,337
We have x-rayed it, sir. There's
nothing whatever concealed in the box.

695
00:34:37,402 --> 00:34:39,552
We'll have a look at the plates.

696
00:34:47,529 --> 00:34:49,592
There must be some clue

697
00:34:49,659 --> 00:34:52,382
and it's probably so obvious
that we've all overlooked it.

698
00:34:52,447 --> 00:34:55,246
Seems to me were up against
a bunch of lunatics.

699
00:34:56,866 --> 00:34:59,059
Not lunatics, my dear fellow,

700
00:34:59,125 --> 00:35:01,228
extremely astute, cold-blooded murderers.

701
00:35:01,294 --> 00:35:02,938
Well, what can these little musical boxes

702
00:35:03,003 --> 00:35:04,767
have in them that's so important?

703
00:35:04,833 --> 00:35:07,186
Don't forget they were
made in Dartmoor Prison.

704
00:35:07,252 --> 00:35:09,975
Why you can smuggle stuff
into prison but not out.

705
00:35:10,041 --> 00:35:11,894
Do you want us to break
the box apart, sir,

706
00:35:11,960 --> 00:35:14,193
to see if there's anything
the x-ray hasn't caught?

707
00:35:14,259 --> 00:35:15,403
No, not yet.

708
00:35:15,469 --> 00:35:16,442
Do you mind if I take it?

709
00:35:16,508 --> 00:35:18,208
- Certainly.
- Thanks.

710
00:35:27,684 --> 00:35:30,037
The governor of Dartmoor
Prison informed us, sir,

711
00:35:30,103 --> 00:35:32,366
in answer to
Mr. Holmes' question

712
00:35:32,432 --> 00:35:35,285
that all three musical boxes
were made by the same convict,

713
00:35:35,351 --> 00:35:37,954
John Davidson, serving a 7-year term, sir.

714
00:35:38,020 --> 00:35:39,793
- Davidson?
- The Bank of England plates.

715
00:35:39,859 --> 00:35:41,549
- That will be all.
- Yes, sir.

716
00:35:42,728 --> 00:35:44,502
Now were getting somewhere.

717
00:35:44,568 --> 00:35:46,001
Wait a minute

718
00:35:46,067 --> 00:35:48,040
how did you know about
the plates, Mr. Holmes?

719
00:35:48,106 --> 00:35:49,920
I'm a student of crime, Inspector.

720
00:35:49,986 --> 00:35:52,089
I make my business to
know about such things

721
00:35:52,155 --> 00:35:54,088
and when the name of
Davidson was mentioned.

722
00:35:54,154 --> 00:35:55,887
Well, who is this fellow Davidson?

723
00:35:55,953 --> 00:35:58,426
As long as Mr. Holmes seems
to know all about it already

724
00:35:58,492 --> 00:36:02,595
I suppose there's no harm in telling you.

725
00:36:02,661 --> 00:36:04,514
Two years ago in London

726
00:36:04,580 --> 00:36:07,513
there occurred a robbery
of such tremendous importance,

727
00:36:07,579 --> 00:36:09,392
although the stolen articles themselves

728
00:36:09,458 --> 00:36:11,391
have no intrinsic value whatsoever,

729
00:36:11,457 --> 00:36:13,021
but the home secretary was instrumental

730
00:36:13,087 --> 00:36:15,810
in seeing that not word of it
appeared in any newspaper.

731
00:36:15,876 --> 00:36:18,979
But you never told me
anything about this, Holmes.

732
00:36:19,045 --> 00:36:20,778
You were away at the time.

733
00:36:20,844 --> 00:36:24,486
Articles of no intrinsic value
and yet of such importance.

734
00:36:24,552 --> 00:36:25,986
I don't understand.

735
00:36:26,052 --> 00:36:27,405
When Davidson was apprehended

736
00:36:27,471 --> 00:36:29,824
within fifteen minutes
of committing the theft

737
00:36:29,890 --> 00:36:32,743
but by that time he'd hidden
the articles in question

738
00:36:32,809 --> 00:36:34,493
and they've yet to be found.

739
00:36:34,559 --> 00:36:36,702
Before going further, Doctor Watson,

740
00:36:36,768 --> 00:36:39,581
I must inform you that this matter is not
to be mentioned outside of this room.

741
00:36:39,647 --> 00:36:42,620
Of course not. Do I look
like a man who'd gossip?

742
00:36:42,686 --> 00:36:45,458
Let's not go into that now,
old fellow, shall we?

743
00:36:45,524 --> 00:36:47,918
Davidson had been employed for years

744
00:36:47,984 --> 00:36:50,037
in a position of extreme trust

745
00:36:50,103 --> 00:36:52,046
by the engravings department
of the Bank of England.

746
00:36:52,112 --> 00:36:54,625
The articles he stole were nothing less

747
00:36:54,691 --> 00:36:56,794
than a complete duplicate set of plates

748
00:36:56,860 --> 00:36:59,463
- for printing five-pound notes.
- What?

749
00:36:59,529 --> 00:37:02,712
- The Bank of England's own plates?
- Precisely.

750
00:37:02,778 --> 00:37:05,471
And with those plates a gang
of crooks could flood England

751
00:37:05,537 --> 00:37:06,800
with five-pound notes,

752
00:37:06,866 --> 00:37:09,049
not forged in the usual sense of the word

753
00:37:09,115 --> 00:37:11,968
but notes undetectable from
genuine Bank of England notes

754
00:37:12,034 --> 00:37:14,347
- in any way whatsoever.
- Good heavens.

755
00:37:14,413 --> 00:37:17,726
Any whisper at all might have
resulted in enormous damage

756
00:37:17,792 --> 00:37:19,685
in shaking public confidence
in the treasury.

757
00:37:19,751 --> 00:37:22,264
We tried everything after
we arrested Davidson.

758
00:37:22,330 --> 00:37:23,604
Offered him a shorter sentence

759
00:37:23,670 --> 00:37:25,023
if he'd tell us where
he'd hidden the plates.

760
00:37:25,089 --> 00:37:27,562
Why we even put in Scotland Yard men

761
